A new course at Harvard University this year makes all S1 students there sleep more, in an effort to counter the macho culture in learning that is developing through caffeine-energy ‘human ghostbirds’.
An academic finds that students at the world’s number one university often don’t know anything if they discuss the very fundamental thing about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of medicine specializing in sleep problems at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving lectures on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
'At last a girl came to me and said, 'Why was I just being told now, in my last year?'
The girl said no one ever told me about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, launched first this year, explains to students the essence of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic outcomes, as well as improving their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s executive director of health services, said that the university decided to introduce the course after finding a student who was severely lacking sleep throughout the week.
This one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one session there is an overview of the bedroom, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sports pants, and books to get an explanation about the influence of caffeine and lights, as well as how athletic results are influenced by lack of sleep, and the importance of sleep routines.
In the other section, participants get an explanation of how long a lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know this won't change the student's behavior immediately.
But we are sure that they have the right to know – as you have the right to know the effects of choosing to smoke on health,” said Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride with ‘sleeping’ still exists, he argues, in addition that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students which means sleep deprivation is a constantly evolving problem.
Ensure that you sleep enough, with good quality, should be a ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, fatigue, and anxiety – even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep makes the brain activate hunger mode, causing constant hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studied chemistry and physical biology who helped Professor Czeisler design the course, had taken one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to organize courses for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes that all graduate students will be instructed to complete a similar study program before joining a competitive institution.
Prof Czeisler recommends that students should consider setting a sleep time alarm, as well as a wake-up alarm, and be aware of the effects of the ‘blue light’ emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can shift your circadian rhythm out of its tracks causing sleep problems.
