Red Tide: Low concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decline in Red Tide concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, uneven accumulation conditions were reported from the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - indicating a decrease in concentrations.
A Red Tide group extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from the north of Pinellas to the southern Lee area.
The groups can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough area, but on some sites relative to last week.
Red Tide has also been observed in the Pasco region.
Concentrations on or off the coast of the Pinellas region have been reported last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of the Hillsborough region, background concentrations up to high in the Manatee region, background concentrations up to high on or off the coast of the Sarasota region, concentrations down to high on the coast of the Hillsborough region, background concentrations up to high in the Manatee region.
Breathing irritation continues to be reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier regions.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation in northwestern Florida last week.
